metadata.name: Pixel Tunnel III #2
metadata.description:
This is based on a technique I've used to create textured abstract art by starting with a base design and applying millions of small mutations.

This design introduces generators and voids.

Generator: A block of color that continually reappears in the same location as the design generates.

Void: A black hole that appears near the end of the generation to break up the design and give visual relief.

- Higher themes are more rare (60 max)
- More colors are more rare (3 min, 6 max)
- Higher generator counts are more rare (5 min)
- There are 5 possible void patterns varying in rarity

metadata.name: Body Politics #5
metadata.description:
We live in a world where hard-fought rights are being used as political playthings.

Choice, Gender, Freedom, Power, Equality and Inclusion are under attack.

‘Body Politics’ takes an abstract view of these issues, and hopefully, we see hope, freedom and beauty in the struggle depicted.  

L to save at 1000x1000 
S to save at 4000x4000
Created with love, in p5js July 2022

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #311
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

License: CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ - @jakub_antolak

metadata.name: Mooncakes: Happy Mid Autumn Festival 2022 #408
metadata.description:
To celebrate the Moon Festival with Mooncakes, we have created a quest to introduce everyone to fxhash. As part of that quest on mooncakes.fun, users are encouraged to mint this generative token.

This is a layered image composition using the Mooncakes site images on a 1920x1080 canvas. The image elements are randomly assigned position, scale, tint, and blur according to a ruleset which generates a Mid Autumn Festival scene made up of: Moon, Clouds, Stars, Lanterns, and Lotuses.

Special filters, shapes and colors are included as rare features, as well as a couple of surprises.

metadata.name: <iframes> #246
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #25
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #2 Moonrise by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Duet #218
metadata.description:
by Daeinc
Aug 2022

Duet explores generative+computational motion and creates an almost infinite sequence of visual compositions. Two groups of shapes transform, merge, and split randomly. What can be disorienting starts to make sense as every element is animated from one to the other. This transition animation is what connects random pieces and creates a relationship between them. Each element is mathematically interpolated, with its motion defined by an equation. 

Although there are key moments, it is hard to summarize time-based work as a static image. As a constantly evolving generative motion piece, Duet invites viewers to form their impression by feeling the rhythm over time.

## Guide:
- The animation responds to window aspect ratio. It reproduces the same outcome at the same ratio. 
- For reliable playback, keep the window active and use IPFS view.
- See browser console for more info.
- Tested on MacOS 12.5.1 with Chromium 104.0

## Keyboard Interaction
- [n] to play a new random loop.
- [spacebar] to play/pause.
- [s] to save PNG. use URL params for dimensions.
- [up] and [down] to change shape resolution.
- [left] and [right] to change BPM. only works while looping. 
- [h] to toggle high DPI mode. off by default.
- [p] to toggle pixel snapping. off by default.

## URL Parameters
- add parameters separated by ampersand to the URL ex. https://.../?fxhash=...&w=1200&h=600
- [w] and [h]: set width and height in pixels. (ex. w=1200&h=600)
- [s] and [e]: set starting and ending keyframes (inclusive) for loop. (ex. s=20&e=24) 
- setting large values for start/end is not advised.
- [len]: instead of start/end, set a loop length between 1 and 16. (ex. len=4)
- [bpm]: beats per minute. (ex. bpm=80)
- [res]: shape resolution between 0 and 18. (ex. res=2)
- [pr]: pixel ratio. set it to 2 (or press [h]) for hi-DPI screens.
- [ar]: maximum aspect ratio. set to any value over 1. 1.2 by default.
- [snap]: add the param to snap to pixel grid.

## License
CC BY-NC 4.0
Please refer to the included LICENSE.md for license information.
Libraries used: canvas-sketch, canvas-sketch-util, dom-events, hsv2rgb, keyframes, equations from easings.net, array shuffle from stackoverflow.

metadata.name: Flustels #81
metadata.description:
Fully generative artwork in crayoning style.

The model uses Perlin noise map multiplied by map with flowers.
Each flower generated randomly with circles and ellipses. 

Each token is 100% unique.

Traits:
- 20 color palettes;
- 5 compositions;
- 9 background styles;
- 2 brush weights.

Press 's' to save .png with resolution 2000px * 2000px.

Renders fastest in Chrome browser.

Made with p5js, math and love by @ivposure

metadata.name: blinksquare 2022 #109
metadata.description:
From the pixel-lab vault - evolved from 'blinksquare' (2008) 
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Mouse-click switches between:
- screen scaled image
- The large image (for printing)

Right-click: Save/Copy the image

A custom created 'soft' pixel 2D/3D engine,
written in vanilla JavaScript some more info in the source-code
- The work will refresh and restart after some time -
-------------------------------------------------

I created 'blinksquare' back in 2008 in Secondlife,
it was like a kinetic 3D sculpture; that would change over time.

I wanted to do a 2022 remake; and while working on it; it evolved a bit.
Also inspired by writing and ancient Hieroglyphs from around the world 


xxx Amsterdam chillout
